Dynamic SOQL — The Complete Picture
What it is and why it exists

Every SOQL query you've written so far has been static — enclosed in square brackets, with the object, fields, and filters fixed at compile time:

apex
List<Account> accts = [SELECT Id, Name FROM Account WHERE Industry = 'Tech'];

The compiler validates this at save time. If you misspell Industry or the field gets deleted, the code won't even compile. That's a huge safety net.

Dynamic SOQL gives that safety net up in exchange for flexibility: you build the query as an ordinary String at runtime and execute it with Database.query().
Nothing about it is checked until the moment it runs.

When do you genuinely need this?

User-driven filters — a search page where the user picks which fields to filter on and what values to use. You can't write a static query for every combination.
Configurable object or field names — a generic utility that works on any sObject ("export any object to CSV," "audit any object's records"), or field names stored in Custom Metadata.
Conditionally assembled clauses — the WHERE clause has 2 pieces sometimes and 6 pieces other times, depending on inputs.
Managed packages / frameworks — code that must run in orgs whose schema you don't know at build time.

If the query can be static, make it static. Dynamic SOQL is the fallback, not the default — you lose compile-time validation, you take on injection risk, and the code is harder to read. 
That's the rule of thumb to carry.

**********************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************

The core mechanism: Database.query()
apex
String q = 'SELECT Id, Name FROM Account LIMIT 10';
List<Account> accts = Database.query(q);

Things to know about the return value:

Its declared return type is List<sObject>, but Apex will happily assign it to List<Account> if the query is on Account — the runtime does the cast. 
If the object type isn't known until runtime, keep it as List<sObject>.
It counts against the same governor limits as static SOQL: same 100-queries-per-transaction cap, same 50,000-row limit. Dynamic vs. static makes no difference to the limits engine.
If the string is malformed, or references a field/object that doesn't exist, you get a runtime QueryException (or System.QueryException: unexpected token…). 
This is the compile-time-safety trade-off made concrete: errors that static SOQL would catch at save time now surface in production at execution time.

Working with results generically, when you don't know the type:

apex
List<sObject> rows = Database.query(q);
for (sObject row : rows) {
    Id recId     = (Id) row.get('Id');
    String name  = (String) row.get('Name');      // generic field access
    // For parent traversal on generic sObjects:
    sObject parent = row.getSObject('Account');    // e.g. on a Contact row
}

get('FieldName') returns Object, so you cast — this is the generic counterpart of contact.Account.Name dot notation.

*************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************

Bind variables in dynamic SOQL

This is the single most important thing to internalize. A bind variable (:varName) in a dynamic query string is not string interpolation. 
The variable is not pasted into the string. 
Instead, at execution time, the SOQL engine resolves :varName against the local Apex scope and passes the value through a safe, typed channel — exactly like a prepared statement parameter in JDBC.

apex
String targetIndustry = 'Technology';
Decimal minRevenue = 500000;

String q = 'SELECT Id, Name FROM Account ' +
           'WHERE Industry = :targetIndustry AND AnnualRevenue > :minRevenue';

List<Account> accts = Database.query(q);   // binds resolve here

Why this matters so much:

1.Security. A bound value can never break out of its position and alter the query structure. Even if targetIndustry contained 'Tech\' OR Name != null', 
it would be treated as a literal string to compare against, not as SOQL syntax. Injection is structurally impossible through a bind.
2.Correctness. Binds handle typing and escaping for you. Dates, Datetimes, Booleans, Ids, quotes inside strings — all formatted correctly without you thinking about it.
3.Collections work too. WHERE Id IN :myIdSet binds a whole Set<Id> or List<String>. Try building that as a string yourself and you'll appreciate this.

The classic limitation: the bind must be a variable in scope at the point where Database.query() executes, 
and it must be a simple variable reference — you can't bind an expression or a method call (:someObj.getValue() fails; assign it to a local first). 
Historically this also meant helper methods that built query strings couldn't carry their binds with them, which is exactly the problem queryWithBinds solves (below).
***********************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************
1. Use a bind whenever possible — including for LIKE, by building the pattern in Apex first:

apex
String pattern = '%' + searchBox + '%';
String q = 'SELECT Id FROM Contact WHERE LastName LIKE :pattern';
List<Contact> rows = Database.query(q);

This is fully safe and is almost always achievable for values. Notice the trick: the wildcards go into the Apex variable, not the query string, so the whole thing rides through the bind.

2. If you truly must concatenate a value, escape it:

apex
String safe = String.escapeSingleQuotes(userInput);
String q = 'SELECT Id FROM Contact WHERE LastName = \'' + safe + '\'';

escapeSingleQuotes prefixes every ' with \, so the input can't terminate the string literal and inject syntax. Understand its limits, though: it only protects quoted string values. 
It does nothing for numbers, dates, or booleans concatenated without quotes, and nothing for structural elements.

3. For object/field names (which can never be bound or quoted), validate against the schema:

apex
String objName = configuredObjectName;   // from user or metadata

// Whitelist approach — does this object actually exist, and is it queryable?
Schema.SObjectType t = Schema.getGlobalDescribe().get(objName);
if (t == null || !t.getDescribe().isQueryable()) {
    throw new IllegalArgumentException('Invalid object: ' + objName);
}

// Field-level check
Map<String, Schema.SObjectField> fields = t.getDescribe().fields.getMap();
if (!fields.containsKey(fieldName)) {
    throw new IllegalArgumentException('Invalid field: ' + fieldName);
}

String q = 'SELECT Id, ' + fieldName + ' FROM ' + objName;

Binds can only carry values, never identifiers — you cannot write FROM :objName. So identifiers must be concatenated, and the only safe way to concatenate them is to first prove they're legitimate schema members. 
An even stricter approach is an explicit allow-list (Set<String> allowed = new Set<String>{'Account','Contact'};).

The mental model: values → bind; can't bind → escape; identifiers → validate against describe/allow-list.

Database.queryWithBinds() — explicit bind maps

Added in API 57.0 (Spring '23), this solves the scope-resolution weakness of classic binds. Instead of the engine hunting for :key in your local variables, you hand it a Map<String, Object>:

apex
Map<String, Object> binds = new Map<String, Object>{
    'ind'    => 'Technology',
    'minRev' => 500000,
    'ids'    => new Set<Id>{'001...', '001...'}
};

String q = 'SELECT Id, Name FROM Account ' +
           'WHERE Industry = :ind AND AnnualRevenue > :minRev AND Id IN :ids';

List<Account> accts = Database.queryWithBinds(q, binds, AccessLevel.USER_MODE);

Why this is a real improvement:

The binds travel with the query. A QueryBuilder helper class can now construct both the string and its bind map and return them together; the caller doesn't need magic local variables with matching names.
This makes reusable query-building code actually clean.
Keys are explicit, so there's no accidental capture of some unrelated in-scope variable.
The third argument, AccessLevel, is required: AccessLevel.SYSTEM_MODE (traditional Apex behavior — object/field permissions ignored) or AccessLevel.USER_MODE (the query respects the running user's object permissions,
field-level security, and sharing rules). 
For anything driven by user input, USER_MODE is the modern best practice — it turns "did I remember to check FLS?" into platform-enforced behavior.

Note the map values replace scope resolution entirely — in a queryWithBinds call, :ind looks only in the map, never at local variables.

Database.getQueryLocator() — the Batch Apex variant

Same input (a query string, or even an inline static query), completely different purpose:

apex
public class MyBatch implements Database.Batchable<sObject> {
    public Database.QueryLocator start(Database.BatchableContext bc) {
        String q = 'SELECT Id, Name FROM Account WHERE LastActivityDate < LAST_N_DAYS:365';
        return Database.getQueryLocator(q);
    }
    public void execute(Database.BatchableContext bc, List<Account> scope) { /* ... */ }
    public void finish(Database.BatchableContext bc) { /* ... */ }
}

The distinction that matters:

Database.query() materializes results immediately and is subject to the 50,000-row limit.
Database.getQueryLocator() returns a cursor, not records. In a batch start() method it can drive up to 50 million records, which the platform then feeds to execute() in chunks. 
It's how you do dynamic SOQL over huge datasets.

Outside Batch Apex, a query locator also powers Database.getQueryLocator(...).iterator() in some streaming scenarios, but batch start() is 95% of its real-world use.

There's also a fourth sibling worth knowing: Database.countQuery() (and countQueryWithBinds()), for dynamic aggregate counts without retrieving rows:

apex
Integer n = Database.countQuery('SELECT COUNT() FROM Account WHERE Industry = :ind');

A realistic end-to-end example: a filter builder

This is the pattern dynamic SOQL exists for — assembling a query from optional user filters, safely:

apex
public with sharing class AccountSearchService {

    public static List<Account> search(String nameTerm, String industry, Decimal minRevenue) {
        List<String> conditions = new List<String>();
        Map<String, Object> binds = new Map<String, Object>();

        if (String.isNotBlank(nameTerm)) {
            conditions.add('Name LIKE :namePattern');
            binds.put('namePattern', '%' + nameTerm + '%');   // wildcard lives in the VALUE
        }
        if (String.isNotBlank(industry)) {
            conditions.add('Industry = :ind');
            binds.put('ind', industry);
        }
        if (minRevenue != null) {
            conditions.add('AnnualRevenue >= :minRev');
            binds.put('minRev', minRevenue);
        }

        String q = 'SELECT Id, Name, Industry, AnnualRevenue FROM Account';
        if (!conditions.isEmpty()) {
            q += ' WHERE ' + String.join(conditions, ' AND ');
        }
        q += ' ORDER BY Name LIMIT 200';

        return Database.queryWithBinds(q, binds, AccessLevel.USER_MODE);
    }
}

Notice what makes this safe and clean: every user-supplied value goes through the bind map (zero concatenation of input), the structural parts of the query are fixed string literals I control, 
conditions compose via a List<String> + String.join, and USER_MODE enforces FLS/sharing on top. 
This is the template to reuse whenever you build filterable queries.
*********************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************

Limitations and gotchas checklist

No compile-time validation. A schema change (someone deletes a field) breaks dynamic queries silently until runtime. Mitigate with test coverage that actually executes the query paths.
Bind expressions must be simple variables in classic Database.query() — no :obj.field, no :method(). Assign to a local first, or use queryWithBinds.
You can't bind identifiers — object names, field names, ORDER BY directions. Those must be validated/allow-listed and concatenated.
escapeSingleQuotes only protects quoted string contexts. It is not a general sanitizer.
Same governor limits as static SOQL — going dynamic buys you zero extra headroom.
Security modes: old code often relied on WITH SECURITY_ENFORCED inside the query string; the modern replacements are AccessLevel.USER_MODE (on queryWithBinds/query overloads) or Security.stripInaccessible() on the results. Prefer USER_MODE in new code.
Testing tip: because errors are runtime, write tests for the malformed paths too — assert that invalid field names throw your validation exception rather than leaking a raw QueryException to users.

The one-paragraph summary to file away: dynamic SOQL is a String executed by Database.query() (or queryWithBinds with an explicit bind map and access level, or getQueryLocator for batch-scale). 
Values always go through binds; anything that can't be bound gets escaped; identifiers get validated against the schema; and USER_MODE handles the permission layer. 
Reach for it only when the query genuinely can't be known at compile time.

Want to make this stick with a practice exercise — say, extending that AccountSearchService to support dynamic ORDER BY and field selection safely? 
That forces you through the identifier-validation problem, which is the trickiest part in real code.
**************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************
1. Search box concatenated straight into WHERE

The textbook case — a user-controlled search term pasted into the query string.

apex
// ❌ VULNERABLE
String term = ApexPages.currentPage().getParameters().get('q');
String query = 'SELECT Id FROM Contact WHERE LastName = \'' + term + '\'';
List<Contact> results = Database.query(query);

Input x' OR Name != ' turns the filter into LastName = 'x' OR Name != '' — every contact returned.

apex
// ✅ FIXED — bind variable, no concatenation
String term = ApexPages.currentPage().getParameters().get('q');
String query = 'SELECT Id FROM Contact WHERE LastName = :term';
List<Contact> results = Database.query(query);

The value now rides through a typed, safe channel and can never alter query structure. Binding is always the first choice.
*****************************************************************************************************************************
2. LIKE search with wildcards

People correctly reach for LIKE but then concatenate, thinking the % makes binding impossible.

apex
// ❌ VULNERABLE
String term = getUserInput();
String query = 'SELECT Id FROM Account WHERE Name LIKE \'%' + term + '%\'';
List<Account> a = Database.query(query);
apex
// ✅ FIXED — put the wildcards in the Apex value, then bind
String term = getUserInput();
String pattern = '%' + term + '%';        // wildcards live in the variable
String query = 'SELECT Id FROM Account WHERE Name LIKE :pattern';
List<Account> a = Database.query(query);

The trick most people miss: build the wildcard pattern in Apex and bind the whole thing. No escaping needed.
***************************************************************************************************************************
3. Value that genuinely must be concatenated

Occasionally you're stuck concatenating a string value (some dynamic-clause builders). Then — and only then — escape it.

apex
// ❌ VULNERABLE
String status = getStatusFilter();
String query = 'SELECT Id FROM Case WHERE Status = \'' + status + '\'';
apex
// ✅ FIXED — String.escapeSingleQuotes as the fallback
String status = String.escapeSingleQuotes(getStatusFilter());
String query = 'SELECT Id FROM Case WHERE Status = \'' + status + '\'';

escapeSingleQuotes backslash-escapes every ', so the input can't terminate the literal. Caveat: it only protects quoted string contexts — it does nothing for the next three scenarios.
******************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************
4. Dynamic object or field name (identifiers can't be bound)

Binds carry values, never identifiers. FROM :objName is illegal, so people concatenate — and escaping doesn't help because there are no quotes to escape.

apex
// ❌ VULNERABLE
String obj = getConfiguredObject();
String query = 'SELECT Id, Name FROM ' + obj;   // obj = 'Account WHERE Id != null LIMIT 1 FOR UPDATE' ...
apex
// ✅ FIXED — validate against the schema (whitelist by describe)
String obj = getConfiguredObject();
Schema.SObjectType t = Schema.getGlobalDescribe().get(obj);
if (t == null || !t.getDescribe().isQueryable()) {
    throw new IllegalArgumentException('Invalid object: ' + obj);
}
String query = 'SELECT Id, Name FROM ' + String.valueOf(t);
List<sObject> rows = Database.query(query);

For identifiers the defense is validation, not escaping — prove it's a real, queryable object before it goes in the string. 
Same pattern for field names via t.getDescribe().fields.getMap().containsKey(fieldName).
*******************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************
5. Dynamic ORDER BY

A sortable table where the user picks the column. ORDER BY can't be bound, and this is a favorite injection vector because people forget it's user-controlled.

apex
// ❌ VULNERABLE
String sortField = getSortColumn();
String query = 'SELECT Id, Name FROM Account ORDER BY ' + sortField;
apex
// ✅ FIXED — allow-list the permitted columns and direction
Set<String> allowedFields = new Set<String>{'Name', 'Industry', 'CreatedDate', 'AnnualRevenue'};
String sortField = getSortColumn();
String dir = getSortDir() == 'DESC' ? 'DESC' : 'ASC';   // constrain to two values

if (!allowedFields.contains(sortField)) {
    throw new IllegalArgumentException('Invalid sort field');
}
String query = 'SELECT Id, Name FROM Account ORDER BY ' + sortField + ' ' + dir;

An explicit Set allow-list is cleaner and stricter than a describe check when the valid set is known and small.
******************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************
6. Numeric / non-string values (escaping does nothing)

A subtle one: escapeSingleQuotes on a number is useless because there are no quotes — the value sits bare in the query.

apex
// ❌ VULNERABLE — no quotes to escape; escaping this is theater
String limitParam = getUserLimit();   // '5 OR Name != null'
String query = 'SELECT Id FROM Account WHERE NumberOfEmployees > ' + limitParam;
apex
// ✅ FIXED — bind (best), or type-coerce to prove it's numeric
Integer safeLimit = Integer.valueOf(getUserLimit());   // throws if not a number
String query = 'SELECT Id FROM Account WHERE NumberOfEmployees > :safeLimit';
List<Account> a = Database.query(query);

Either bind it, or force it through Integer.valueOf()/Decimal.valueOf() so a non-numeric payload throws before it can reach the query.
***********************************************************************************************************************************************************************************
7. IN-clause built by string-joining a list

Hand-assembling an IN (...) list from user values is a classic footgun — every element is an injection point.

apex
// ❌ VULNERABLE
List<String> names = getUserNames();
String inClause = '(\'' + String.join(names, '\',\'') + '\')';
String query = 'SELECT Id FROM Contact WHERE LastName IN ' + inClause;
apex
// ✅ FIXED — bind the collection directly
List<String> names = getUserNames();
String query = 'SELECT Id FROM Contact WHERE LastName IN :names';   // bind the whole List
List<Contact> c = Database.query(query);

SOQL binds entire List/Set collections into IN clauses natively. Never build the parenthesized list by hand.
***************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************
8. Query built in a helper method (the classic bind-scope trap)

Binds resolve against scope at execution — so a query string assembled in one method and executed in another loses its binds, tempting people to concatenate.

apex
// ❌ VULNERABLE — value concatenated because :term isn't in scope where query runs
public String buildQuery(String term) {
    return 'SELECT Id FROM Lead WHERE Company = \'' + term + '\'';
}
List<Lead> l = Database.query(buildQuery(userInput));
apex
// ✅ FIXED — Database.queryWithBinds carries binds explicitly
public class QuerySpec { public String soql; public Map<String,Object> binds; }

public QuerySpec buildQuery(String term) {
    QuerySpec spec = new QuerySpec();
    spec.soql = 'SELECT Id FROM Lead WHERE Company = :term';
    spec.binds = new Map<String, Object>{ 'term' => term };
    return spec;
}
QuerySpec spec = buildQuery(userInput);
List<Lead> l = Database.queryWithBinds(spec.soql, spec.binds, AccessLevel.USER_MODE);

queryWithBinds (API 57.0+) decouples binds from local scope, which removes the very reason people concatenate in builder methods.
***************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************
9. Second-order injection (stored value used later)

The value looks trusted because it came from the database — but it was originally user input, stored earlier without sanitization.

apex
// ❌ VULNERABLE — cfg.Filter_Clause__c was populated from a user form earlier
Configuration__c cfg = [SELECT Filter_Clause__c FROM Configuration__c LIMIT 1];
String query = 'SELECT Id FROM Account WHERE ' + cfg.Filter_Clause__c;
apex
// ✅ FIXED — treat stored data as untrusted; bind the value, fix the structure
Configuration__c cfg = [SELECT Filter_Value__c FROM Configuration__c LIMIT 1];
String val = cfg.Filter_Value__c;
String query = 'SELECT Id FROM Account WHERE Industry = :val';   // structure is fixed, value bound
List<Account> a = Database.query(query);

The lesson: "came from the database" is not the same as "safe." Store discrete values (bindable), never raw query fragments. If you must store clause structure, validate it against an allow-list on the way out.
******************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************
10. Ignoring permissions — the "injection-adjacent" leak

Not classic injection, but the same root cause (untrusted flow reaching data): dynamic queries run in system mode by default, bypassing the user's FLS and sharing. A user can read fields/records they shouldn't.

apex
// ❌ LEAKY — runs in system mode, ignores FLS + sharing
String query = 'SELECT Id, Salary__c FROM Employee__c WHERE Name = :name';
List<Employee__c> emps = Database.query(query);   // exposes Salary__c even if user can't see it
apex
// ✅ FIXED — enforce the running user's permissions
String query = 'SELECT Id, Salary__c FROM Employee__c WHERE Name = :name';
List<Employee__c> emps = Database.queryWithBinds(
    query, new Map<String,Object>{'name' => name}, AccessLevel.USER_MODE
);
// or on the results:  Security.stripInaccessible(AccessType.READABLE, emps).getRecords();

AccessLevel.USER_MODE makes the platform enforce object permissions, FLS, and sharing — turning a manual "did I check FLS?" into an guarantee. 
Pair it with the injection defenses above; a query can be injection-proof and still leak data if it runs in system mode.
***************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************

The whole thing collapses into a short decision procedure you can apply to any dynamic query:

Is the untrusted input a…                                    	Defense
Value (string, number, date, collection)	                    Bind it (:var / queryWithBinds) — always prefer this
Value you're forced to concatenate	                          String.escapeSingleQuotes() — quoted strings only
Identifier (object / field name)	                            Validate against Schema describe
ORDER BY / direction / operator	                              Allow-list the permitted values
Stored value that was once user input	                        Treat as untrusted → bind or validate
Any dynamic query touching sensitive data	                    Add AccessLevel.USER_MODE
